$$
\begin{gathered}
\mathrm{p}+\mathrm{p} \rightarrow \mathrm{D}+\mathrm{e}^{+}+\nu_{\mathrm{e}} \\
\mathrm{D}+\mathrm{p} \rightarrow { }^{3} \mathrm{He}+\gamma \\
{ }^{3} \mathrm{He}+{ }^{3} \mathrm{He} \rightarrow { }^{4} \mathrm{He}+2 \mathrm{p}
\end{gathered}
$$

总反应为

$$
4 \mathrm{p} \rightarrow { }^{4} \mathrm{He}+2 \mathrm{e}^{+}+2 \nu_{\mathrm{e}}
$$

此反应放出的能量近似为

$$
Q=\left[4 M\left({ }^{1} \mathrm{H}\right)-M\left({ }^{4} \mathrm{He}\right)\right] c^{2} \approx 26.7\,\text{MeV}
$$

If we consider protons as an ideal gas, the proton spins can have two orientations, with energies given by:  
When spin is parallel to \(\boldsymbol{B}\), \( E_{\mathrm{p}}=-\mu_{\mathrm{p}} B \)  
When spin is antiparallel to \(\boldsymbol{B}\), \( E_{\mathrm{p}}=+\mu_{\mathrm{p}} B \)  
Where \(\mu_{\mathrm{p}}=\frac{1}{2} g_{\mathrm{p}} \cdot \mu_{\mathrm{N}}=\frac{1}{2} g_{\mathrm{p}} \frac{e \hbar}{2 m_{\mathrm{p}}}\) is the proton magnetic moment. Given that the proton number density \( n \propto \exp \left(\frac{-E_{\mathrm{p}}}{k T}\right) \), we have 

$$
\begin{gathered}
\frac{\exp \left(\frac{\mu_{\mathrm{p}} B}{k T}\right)-\exp \left(-\frac{\mu_{\mathrm{p}} B}{k T}\right)}{\exp \left(\frac{\mu_{\mathrm{p}} B}{k T}\right)+\exp \left(-\frac{\mu_{\mathrm{p}} B}{k T}\right)}=10^{-4} \\
\quad \text {or equivalently, } \exp \left(\frac{2 \mu_{\mathrm{p}} B}{k T}\right)=\frac{1+10^{-4}}{1-10^{-4}}
\end{gathered}
$$

Thus,

$$
\begin{gathered}
\frac{2 \mu_{\mathrm{p}} B}{k T} \approx 2 \times 10^{-4} \\
B=\frac{k T}{\mu_{\mathrm{p}}} \times 10^{-4}
\end{gathered}
$$

Using the Breit-Wigner formula

$$
\sigma_{\mathrm{n}} = \pi \lambda^{2} \frac{\Gamma_{\mathrm{n}} \Gamma}{\left(E - E_{0}\right)^{2} + \Gamma^{2} / 4}
$$

where $\lambda$ is the reduced wavelength, $E$ is the total energy of the incident neutron and the $^{3}\mathrm{He}$ system relative to the $^{4}\mathrm{He}$ ground state energy, $E_{0}$ is the resonant energy peak of $^{4}\mathrm{He}$, $\Gamma$ is the total width of the resonance decay, and $\Gamma_{\mathrm{n}}$ is the partial width of the resonance decay into neutrons. Using this equation, the resonance capture cross-section of $^{3}\mathrm{He}$ for thermal neutrons can be calculated. For thermal neutrons in the laboratory, $E_{\mathrm{n}} = 0.025 \, \mathrm{eV}$, giving

$$
\begin{aligned}
\lambda & = \frac{\hbar}{\sqrt{2 \mu E_{\mathrm{n}}}} = \frac{\hbar}{\sqrt{2 \frac{m_{\mathrm{n}} m_{3_{\mathrm{He}}}}{m_{\mathrm{n}} + m_{3_{\mathrm{He}}}} E_{\mathrm{n}}}} = \frac{ch}{\sqrt{\frac{3}{2} E_{\mathrm{n}} m_{\mathrm{n}} c^{2}}} \\
& = \frac{197 \times 10^{-13}}{\sqrt{1.5 \times 940 \times 25 \times 10^{-9}}} = 3.3 \times 10^{-9} \, \text{cm}
\end{aligned}
$$

Since the spin and parity of both the excited and ground states of $^{4}\mathrm{He}$ are $J^{\pi}=0^{+}$, $\Gamma_{\gamma}=0$, the only other decay channel for $^{4}\mathrm{He}$ is decay into a proton, i.e., $\Gamma = \Gamma_{\mathrm{n}} + \Gamma_{\mathrm{p}}$. It is found that $\Gamma_{\mathrm{n}} \approx 150 \mathrm{eV}$, $\Gamma = \Gamma_{\mathrm{n}} + \Gamma_{\mathrm{p}} \approx \Gamma_{\mathrm{p}} = 1.2 \mathrm{MeV}$. From Figure 2.56, we know $E = 20.6 \mathrm{MeV}, E_{0} = 20.1 \mathrm{MeV}$, and finally obtain

$$
\begin{aligned}
\sigma & = \pi \lambda^{2} \frac{\Gamma_{\mathrm{n}} \Gamma}{\left(E - E_{0}\right)^{2} + \Gamma^{2} / 4} \\
& = 3.1416 \times 3.3^{2} \times 10^{-18} \times \frac{150 \times 10^{-6} \times 1.2}{(20.6 - 20.1)^{2} + 1.2^{2} / 4} \\
& \approx 1 \times 10^{-20} \, \text{cm}^{2} = 1 \times 10^{4} \, \text{b}
\end{aligned}
$$

For the average helicity of the muon in the laboratory frame $h=0$, it requires that $\boldsymbol{\beta}_{\pi} \cdot \boldsymbol{\beta}_{\mu} = -\beta_{\mu}^{2}$, or $\beta_{\pi} \cos \theta = -\beta_{\mu}$, which implies

$$
\begin{gathered}
\beta_{\pi} \geqslant \beta_{\mu} \quad \text{or} \quad \gamma_{\pi} \geqslant \gamma_{\mu}. \\
\frac{E_{\pi}}{m_{\pi}} \geqslant \frac{m_{\pi}^{2} + m_{\mu}^{2}}{2 m_{\pi} m_{\mu}}
\end{gathered}
$$

Therefore, the required minimum energy for the pion is

$$
\left(E_{\pi}\right)_{\min} = \gamma_{\mu} m_{\pi} = \frac{m_{\pi}^{2} + m_{\mu}^{2}}{2 m_{\mu}}
$$

